00:56:28.350 --> 00:56:30.730
AUDIENCE: That's true.

00:56:30.730 --> 00:56:32.550
So proof of stake is the coins--

00:56:32.550 --> 00:56:35.370
all the coins are already
dispersed onto the network,

00:56:35.370 --> 00:56:43.230
and the verification allocation
is allocated based on--

00:56:43.230 --> 00:56:46.220
GARY GENSLER: So proof of stake
is an alternative consensus

00:56:46.220 --> 00:56:48.530
mechanism.

00:56:48.530 --> 00:56:50.850
And Bo described it well.

00:56:50.850 --> 00:56:54.080
But Kelly, it's not
related to this chart here.

00:56:54.080 --> 00:56:57.170
This is all proof of work.

00:56:57.170 --> 00:57:01.750
BTC has 19% of the hash rate.

00:57:01.750 --> 00:57:05.880
That means that they
literally have about--

00:57:05.880 --> 00:57:11.720
if the total hash power
on Bitcoin is 60 hexa--

00:57:11.720 --> 00:57:12.860
do I have the word--

00:57:12.860 --> 00:57:14.741
AUDIENCE: It starts
with an e-x--

00:57:14.741 --> 00:57:15.241
exa.

00:57:15.241 --> 00:57:19.342
GARY GENSLER: Exahash-- then
19% of that, or about 12.

00:57:19.342 --> 00:57:21.300
AUDIENCE: That's what
they're attempting to do.

00:57:21.300 --> 00:57:23.640
That's not the stake
that they already have.

00:57:23.640 --> 00:57:25.050
GARY GENSLER: Correct.

00:57:25.050 --> 00:57:29.360
Most Bitcoin miners
sell their coins.

00:57:29.360 --> 00:57:32.260
So the coins that are created--

00:57:32.260 --> 00:57:36.460
the coins that are
created each year

00:57:36.460 --> 00:57:42.880
are sold into the
broad community.

00:57:42.880 --> 00:57:46.660
Very few miners hold
onto their coins

00:57:46.660 --> 00:57:49.313
for great lengths of time.

00:57:49.313 --> 00:57:50.480
I mean, they might for days.

00:57:50.480 --> 00:57:55.130
That might for-- they might keep
some for all sorts of reasons.

00:57:55.130 --> 00:57:59.440
And as I truly believe,
but can't factually prove,

00:57:59.440 --> 00:58:02.900
a number of the biggest
mining pools or miners

00:58:02.900 --> 00:58:06.620
are in places where they're
doing illicit activity.

00:58:06.620 --> 00:58:08.120
They're getting
their electricity

00:58:08.120 --> 00:58:11.570
for less than what it's
really costing on the grid

00:58:11.570 --> 00:58:13.415
by bad actors.

00:58:16.670 --> 00:58:18.980
But nonetheless,
they have a choice

00:58:18.980 --> 00:58:21.260
whether to sell their
coins or keep their coins.

00:58:21.260 --> 00:58:23.750
Got a question over here, and
then I want to keep going.

00:58:23.750 --> 00:58:26.520
AUDIENCE: If the mining
industry is like so formalized,

00:58:26.520 --> 00:58:28.880
like you've so many
pools, what prevents

00:58:28.880 --> 00:58:31.620
all the pools from coming
together and saying that,

00:58:31.620 --> 00:58:35.120
let's just solve lesser puzzles
so that the value becomes

00:58:35.120 --> 00:58:36.832
lower, and then the
charge is much lower

00:58:36.832 --> 00:58:37.790
for each and every one?

00:58:37.790 --> 00:58:39.165
GARY GENSLER: So
the question is,

00:58:39.165 --> 00:58:42.110
is what happens if the
mining pools collude and come

00:58:42.110 --> 00:58:47.630
together, either, as
[INAUDIBLE] says, to, let's

00:58:47.630 --> 00:58:55.040
say, well, why should we
have so much mining capacity?

00:58:55.040 --> 00:58:56.210
Let's, as a cartel--

00:58:56.210 --> 00:58:58.700
like OPEC, the oil cartel--

00:58:58.700 --> 00:59:03.590
say we should constrain
supply and so forth.

00:59:03.590 --> 00:59:08.870
I think what constrains
that is it's an open system.

00:59:08.870 --> 00:59:10.040
But it's possible.

00:59:10.040 --> 00:59:11.073
It's plausible.

00:59:11.073 --> 00:59:12.740
I think the bigger
question, and there's

00:59:12.740 --> 00:59:16.280
been numerous academic
papers around this,

00:59:16.280 --> 00:59:19.310
is what happens if the mining
pools come together and try

00:59:19.310 --> 00:59:22.370
to do what's called
a 51% attack,

00:59:22.370 --> 00:59:26.080
and try to take
over the blockchain?

00:59:26.080 --> 00:59:28.280
And that's a more
interesting challenge.

00:59:28.280 --> 00:59:33.600
And we'll talk about that
throughout the semester.

00:59:33.600 --> 00:59:37.750
It hasn't happened as of yet.

00:59:37.750 --> 00:59:40.160
Let me talk about the
native currencies.

00:59:40.160 --> 00:59:42.740
Native currency
helps do all this.

00:59:42.740 --> 00:59:45.578
What Nakamoto said, is it
was an incentive system.

00:59:45.578 --> 00:59:47.495
There was an incentive
system, but it was also

00:59:47.495 --> 00:59:50.570
a peer-to-peer way to
create a new money.

00:59:50.570 --> 00:59:56.330
And embedded in most
blockchains, not 100% of them,

00:59:56.330 --> 00:59:59.540
there is something, I put quotes
around it, monetary policy,

00:59:59.540 --> 01:00:06.600
in essence, that limits
the supply of the currency.

01:00:06.600 --> 01:00:11.340
Not every blockchain has this,
but the vast majority do.

01:00:11.340 --> 01:00:13.680
And when we start talking
about initial coin offerings,

01:00:13.680 --> 01:00:16.370
you'll find some that don't.

01:00:16.370 --> 01:00:18.680
But Bitcoin limits it.

01:00:18.680 --> 01:00:20.670
And I'm just going
to say what it is.

01:00:20.670 --> 01:00:23.650
It's created in a coinbase
transaction in each block.

01:00:26.470 --> 01:00:29.980
It was initially 50
Bitcoins per block.

01:00:29.980 --> 01:00:35.440
But now, because it's
halved every 210,000 blocks,

01:00:35.440 --> 01:00:38.290
it's just 12 and
one half Bitcoins.

01:00:38.290 --> 01:00:42.040
That's the number of
Bitcoins you earn each time

01:00:42.040 --> 01:00:45.670
if you mine a block that's
approximately $75,000 US

01:00:45.670 --> 01:00:48.400
dollars in value
today, give or take,

01:00:48.400 --> 01:00:52.340
or $80,000, roughly,
to mine a block.

01:00:52.340 --> 01:00:57.380
The inflation rate for
Bitcoin right now is 4.1%.

01:00:57.380 --> 01:01:01.130
So think-- for any of you that
have taken monetary policy

01:01:01.130 --> 01:01:04.340
courses or financial courses
that talk about the Federal

01:01:04.340 --> 01:01:09.640
Reserve, Bitcoin is growing
about 4% a year right now.

01:01:09.640 --> 01:01:14.500
But it halves every
210,000 blocks.

01:01:14.500 --> 01:01:16.770
So the inflation rate
will go down to 2%,

01:01:16.770 --> 01:01:20.640
and then later to about 1%, and
later about a half a percent.

01:01:20.640 --> 01:01:25.290
And it caps around
the year 2040.

01:01:25.290 --> 01:01:28.190
So whether Satoshi was one
person or a team of people,

01:01:28.190 --> 01:01:33.800
back in 2008 they put in
place a monetary policy

01:01:33.800 --> 01:01:37.960
that is hard-coded into
the computer base code,

01:01:37.960 --> 01:01:40.960
and is supposedly going
to be there forever

01:01:40.960 --> 01:01:46.010
to cap Bitcoin at
21 million Bitcoin.

01:01:46.010 --> 01:01:51.700
I'm going to throw up Ether just
because it's an alternative.

01:01:51.700 --> 01:01:54.970
Currently, that mines
three ETH per block.

01:01:54.970 --> 01:01:59.457
And the inflation
rate's about 7 and 1/2%.

01:01:59.457 --> 01:02:01.040
It's a different
stage of development,

01:02:01.040 --> 01:02:03.440
different inflation rate.

01:02:03.440 --> 01:02:06.650
But there has been a proposal
recently to literally--

01:02:06.650 --> 01:02:09.170
it was a proposal
by the programmers,

01:02:09.170 --> 01:02:12.492
we should really lower
the inflation rate.

01:02:12.492 --> 01:02:14.700
And if it's accepted, it
will be adopted in November.

01:02:17.990 --> 01:02:26.890
The fees in Ethereum are largely
paid in something called Gas.

01:02:26.890 --> 01:02:31.150
Gas is just a small
unit of Ethereum.

01:02:31.150 --> 01:02:33.226
What's the small
unit of Bitcoin?

01:02:33.226 --> 01:02:34.020
AUDIENCE: Satoshi.

01:02:34.020 --> 01:02:35.770
GARY GENSLER: Satoshi.

01:02:35.770 --> 01:02:38.600
So Gas and Satoshi
are very similar.

01:02:38.600 --> 01:02:39.365
Brodush.

01:02:39.365 --> 01:02:42.190
AUDIENCE: I think the
limit of 21 million

01:02:42.190 --> 01:02:45.143
has switched to 2140, not 2040.

01:02:45.143 --> 01:02:46.310
GARY GENSLER: It's not 2040?

01:02:46.310 --> 01:02:48.280
AUDIENCE: It's 2140.

01:02:48.280 --> 01:02:50.090
GARY GENSLER: Yes.

01:02:50.090 --> 01:02:50.590
Wait.

01:02:50.590 --> 01:02:53.700
You think it's 2140?

01:02:53.700 --> 01:02:55.417
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

01:02:55.417 --> 01:02:56.500
GARY GENSLER: What's that?

01:02:56.500 --> 01:02:57.708
AUDIENCE: I also [INAUDIBLE].

01:02:57.708 --> 01:02:59.780
GARY GENSLER: All right.

01:02:59.780 --> 01:03:02.560
So I typed poorly.

01:03:02.560 --> 01:03:04.260
Aviva, did you have a question?

01:03:04.260 --> 01:03:05.960
No.

01:03:05.960 --> 01:03:06.460
Alene.

01:03:06.460 --> 01:03:08.170
AUDIENCE: So this is--

01:03:08.170 --> 01:03:10.260
Bitcoin is a
deflationary currency?

01:03:10.260 --> 01:03:11.715
AUDIENCE: Yes.

01:03:11.715 --> 01:03:13.090
GARY GENSLER:
Well, Alene says is

01:03:13.090 --> 01:03:15.430
Bitcoin a deflationary
currency, depending

01:03:15.430 --> 01:03:19.320
upon your use of that word.

01:03:19.320 --> 01:03:21.450
But others have
written that Bitcoin

01:03:21.450 --> 01:03:24.540
is a deflationary currency
because it's not growing.

01:03:24.540 --> 01:03:28.200
If the economy is
growing at x percent,

01:03:28.200 --> 01:03:31.410
and x percent is bigger
than how Bitcoin is growing,

01:03:31.410 --> 01:03:36.900
that would sort of define
it as deflationary.

01:03:36.900 --> 01:03:42.390
I would just note that
those who are fond--

01:03:42.390 --> 01:03:44.260
and there's a lot of
academic literature.

01:03:44.260 --> 01:03:47.370
And this goes back
decades, if not centuries.

01:03:47.370 --> 01:03:51.450
For hard currencies, where
monetary policy is absolutely

01:03:51.450 --> 01:03:55.170
formula-driven, whether it's
the Taylor rule or other rules--

01:03:55.170 --> 01:03:58.410
rule-based monetary
policy would have

01:03:58.410 --> 01:04:02.670
a fondness for what you could
maybe put in computer code.

01:04:02.670 --> 01:04:06.390
Those who think that
humans should be involved,

01:04:06.390 --> 01:04:09.870
and many people
think there is a need

01:04:09.870 --> 01:04:11.970
for some human
involvement, would

01:04:11.970 --> 01:04:15.540
say this is too hard-coded, and
you'd want something where you

01:04:15.540 --> 01:04:17.190
can modify it and change it.

01:04:17.190 --> 01:04:20.580
And that would be
dangerous in times of war,

01:04:20.580 --> 01:04:24.300
in times of stress, in
times of economic peril.

01:04:24.300 --> 01:04:30.480
Or like the 2008 crisis, that
this would make a crisis worse.

01:04:30.480 --> 01:04:33.960
And so the academic literature
and the real life reality

01:04:33.960 --> 01:04:37.500
of the last couple of hundred
years of hard currencies,

01:04:37.500 --> 01:04:40.830
hard monetary policies
versus human involvement

01:04:40.830 --> 01:04:44.100
and some judgment, is kind
of an interesting debate

01:04:44.100 --> 01:04:45.975
that goes right in the
middle of all of this.

01:04:45.975 --> 01:04:47.267
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE] question.

01:04:47.267 --> 01:04:49.110
Would you consider
this as being currency?

01:04:49.110 --> 01:04:51.290
Or is it an asset--

01:04:51.290 --> 01:04:54.698
it's a class of asset that
has some aspect of a currency.

01:04:54.698 --> 01:04:57.240
GARY GENSLER: So the question
is, is this is a real currency,

01:04:57.240 --> 01:05:03.150
or is it just an asset that
has aspects of a currency?

01:05:03.150 --> 01:05:05.550
Ben, what do you think?

01:05:05.550 --> 01:05:07.417
AUDIENCE: So there
were three roles of--

01:05:07.417 --> 01:05:09.500
well, three ways that you
could define a currency.

01:05:09.500 --> 01:05:11.310
It was the unit
of account, stored

01:05:11.310 --> 01:05:15.000
value, and medium of exchange.

01:05:15.000 --> 01:05:16.920
So I guess this has all
of those attributes.

01:05:16.920 --> 01:05:18.645
So you could call it a currency.

01:05:18.645 --> 01:05:20.770
GARY GENSLER: You're saying
if it has all of those.

01:05:20.770 --> 01:05:21.810
AUDIENCE: It does
have those attributes.

01:05:21.810 --> 01:05:22.380
GARY GENSLER: Oh, it does.

01:05:22.380 --> 01:05:23.070
All right.

01:05:23.070 --> 01:05:25.710
So Ben thinks yes.

01:05:25.710 --> 01:05:31.750
How many people are with Ben
as of September 18, 2018,

01:05:31.750 --> 01:05:34.660
not 2118?

01:05:34.660 --> 01:05:36.910
So Isabella's there.

01:05:36.910 --> 01:05:38.900
Zan, Joaquin?

01:05:38.900 --> 01:05:39.810
How many people--

01:05:39.810 --> 01:05:40.370
Tom.

01:05:40.370 --> 01:05:41.570
How many people think not?

01:05:44.620 --> 01:05:48.850
I don't-- I think that you
all get to decide yourself.

01:05:48.850 --> 01:05:54.070
Mark Carney, who's the governor
of the Bank of England,

01:05:54.070 --> 01:05:57.730
gave a speech earlier
in the year, which

01:05:57.730 --> 01:06:00.580
is assigned in a later class.

01:06:00.580 --> 01:06:02.080
And he says, I don't
think we should

01:06:02.080 --> 01:06:03.390
