01:06:03.390 --> 01:06:05.350
They should be
called cryptoassets.

01:06:05.350 --> 01:06:10.490
They're not yet evidencing
all three of these.

01:06:10.490 --> 01:06:13.840
So that's Mark Carney, who
I have great respect for.

01:06:13.840 --> 01:06:17.080
But there are others that say,
no, it's evidencing enough.

01:06:17.080 --> 01:06:18.520
I would say this, though.

01:06:18.520 --> 01:06:20.410
It's plausible that they will--

01:06:20.410 --> 01:06:23.920
and this-- if you take
nothing else from the class,

01:06:23.920 --> 01:06:27.760
it's plausible in my view
that they could provide.

01:06:27.760 --> 01:06:30.910
You could have digital
currency that does not

01:06:30.910 --> 01:06:33.590
have a central authority.

01:06:33.590 --> 01:06:35.900
I mean, I think that
innovation is there.

01:06:35.900 --> 01:06:38.750
Whether you call it a
cryptocurrency or cryptoasset

01:06:38.750 --> 01:06:41.720
at this point in time,
I leave to all of you.

01:06:41.720 --> 01:06:44.540
There won't be a right answer
to that on any paper you submit.

01:06:44.540 --> 01:06:50.500
You can use whichever term
you think fits your thinking.

01:06:50.500 --> 01:06:51.910
I want to talk
about the network.

01:06:51.910 --> 01:06:52.910
We only have 10 minutes.

01:06:52.910 --> 01:06:55.250
But the network is important.

01:06:55.250 --> 01:06:57.260
And a lot of times when
you talk about Bitcoin

01:06:57.260 --> 01:06:59.427
and blockchain, folks aren't
going to talk about it.

01:06:59.427 --> 01:07:04.410
But I want to quickly hit eight
or nine players on the network.

01:07:04.410 --> 01:07:05.530
There are full nodes.

01:07:05.530 --> 01:07:08.050
A full node is a group--

01:07:08.050 --> 01:07:11.210
is a computer, I should say--

01:07:11.210 --> 01:07:15.310
that stores the full
blockchain, and is

01:07:15.310 --> 01:07:17.530
able to validate
all transactions.

01:07:17.530 --> 01:07:19.030
It doesn't have to.

01:07:19.030 --> 01:07:20.470
It's a volunteer thing.

01:07:20.470 --> 01:07:23.180
But it can validate
all transactions.

01:07:23.180 --> 01:07:26.050
A pruning node-- you're not
going to read a lot about it,

01:07:26.050 --> 01:07:27.730
but I just have it.

01:07:27.730 --> 01:07:30.973
It prunes transactions
once they've validated,

01:07:30.973 --> 01:07:32.140
and they have a certain age.

01:07:32.140 --> 01:07:35.110
They're saying, all of
those early transactions,

01:07:35.110 --> 01:07:36.970
we're not going to focus.

01:07:36.970 --> 01:07:44.470
There's been probably six times
the number of transactions

01:07:44.470 --> 01:07:49.240
that have happened compared to
the actual extant transactions

01:07:49.240 --> 01:07:50.110
right now.

01:07:50.110 --> 01:07:52.790
So all the transactions
that have ever happened,

01:07:52.790 --> 01:07:55.450
five, six of them have
already been used.

01:07:55.450 --> 01:07:56.810
They're not around anymore.

01:07:56.810 --> 01:08:00.250
Why do we have to lug it
around in our data set?

01:08:00.250 --> 01:08:03.090
So you could have
a pruning node.

01:08:03.090 --> 01:08:04.980
Lightweight nodes,
which if any of you

01:08:04.980 --> 01:08:07.710
have a Bitcoin wallet
or any other wallet,

01:08:07.710 --> 01:08:09.720
you probably have
a lightweight--

01:08:09.720 --> 01:08:14.060
some form of lightweight node,
or what's called an SPV node.

01:08:14.060 --> 01:08:19.050
It stores just those
blockchain headers, rather than

01:08:19.050 --> 01:08:24.779
all this detail underneath--
a lot less storage.

01:08:24.779 --> 01:08:26.910
But a lightweight
node has to rely

01:08:26.910 --> 01:08:28.833
on the full nodes
for verification,

01:08:28.833 --> 01:08:30.500
because the lightweight
node's not going

01:08:30.500 --> 01:08:32.109
to be doing that on it's own.

01:08:32.109 --> 01:08:35.779
Miners-- we talked about miners.

01:08:35.779 --> 01:08:37.970
I want to just
mention, miners don't

01:08:37.970 --> 01:08:41.960
have to be full
nodes Amanda, you're

01:08:41.960 --> 01:08:48.170
running this mining operation
for the whole class.

