have 20, 30 mining pools,

01:09:54.310 --> 01:09:57.430
which means you have 20, 30
computers which validates

01:09:57.430 --> 01:09:59.290
the newly proposed block.

01:09:59.290 --> 01:10:02.320
And the thing that
everybody wants to believe

01:10:02.320 --> 01:10:04.030
is that these systems
are decentralized,

01:10:04.030 --> 01:10:07.420
and you have thousands
of contributors.

01:10:07.420 --> 01:10:10.450
GARY GENSLER: So I might start
calling you Nouriel Roubini,

01:10:10.450 --> 01:10:11.440
but I won't.

01:10:11.440 --> 01:10:15.160
But Nouriel Roubini, who's
an economist-- he's sometimes

01:10:15.160 --> 01:10:16.770
called Dr. Doom.

01:10:16.770 --> 01:10:20.020
And he likes that phrase,
because he caused downturns

01:10:20.020 --> 01:10:21.780
in the markets.

01:10:21.780 --> 01:10:24.205
There's a later
reading, and I might

01:10:24.205 --> 01:10:25.330
have even done a video of--

01:10:25.330 --> 01:10:28.240
Roubini has this view, that
it's not decentralized,

01:10:28.240 --> 01:10:32.560
and mining pools are an
Achilles heel of the system.

01:10:32.560 --> 01:10:35.050
But the full nodes,
the 10,000 nodes,

01:10:35.050 --> 01:10:36.760
actually still do validation.

01:10:36.760 --> 01:10:39.130
And there's an interesting
social construct

01:10:39.130 --> 01:10:41.080
where there's a
lot of nodes doing,

01:10:41.080 --> 01:10:46.240
in essence, noncompensated
work validating transactions

01:10:46.240 --> 01:10:48.790
beyond Amanda.

01:10:48.790 --> 01:10:50.170
And any miner--

01:10:50.170 --> 01:10:53.890
Andrew could validate
if he wants to.

01:10:53.890 --> 01:10:56.610
So there's a lot of free
riding that goes along,

01:10:56.610 --> 01:10:59.580
and the economics
of free riding.

01:10:59.580 --> 01:11:03.300
And then there's wallets,
which probably 30 or 40 of you

01:11:03.300 --> 01:11:06.000
have on your computer somewhere.

01:11:06.000 --> 01:11:09.330
They store and view and
send all the transactions.

01:11:09.330 --> 01:11:11.595
But importantly, also
create the key pairs.

01:11:14.250 --> 01:11:17.100
So a lot to cover.

01:11:17.100 --> 01:11:19.590
There's one that's not
a node itself at all.

01:11:19.590 --> 01:11:21.873
It's called the mempool,
or the memory pool.

01:11:21.873 --> 01:11:24.040
And we're going to talk
about this more on Thursday.

01:11:24.040 --> 01:11:28.870
But the memory pool stores
all the unconfirmed,

01:11:28.870 --> 01:11:31.930
but yet, already validated.

01:11:31.930 --> 01:11:33.700
So they've been
validated by somebody.

01:11:33.700 --> 01:11:37.000
A transaction goes
out into the network.

01:11:37.000 --> 01:11:41.200
A full node validates it, and
it's put in a memory pool.

01:11:41.200 --> 01:11:43.480
And Amanda grabs
the memory pool,

01:11:43.480 --> 01:11:47.337
and sends it out to everybody
in this class in a block.

01:11:47.337 --> 01:11:48.170
And then we mine it.

01:11:50.770 --> 01:11:53.810
We're not going to chat
much about these right now.

01:11:53.810 --> 01:11:55.030
