01:11:56.740 --> 01:11:59.920
How many of you actually
skimmed it, looked at it?

01:11:59.920 --> 01:12:01.900
Did it mean anything
to you, or just meant

01:12:01.900 --> 01:12:05.750
that there's some alternative?

01:12:05.750 --> 01:12:06.590
What's that, Prya?

01:12:06.590 --> 01:12:08.260
AUDIENCE: Just that
there's some alternative.

01:12:08.260 --> 01:12:09.885
GARY GENSLER: There's
some alternative.

01:12:09.885 --> 01:12:12.250
That's what it meant to
me the first time I looked

01:12:12.250 --> 01:12:14.260
into this about six months ago.

01:12:14.260 --> 01:12:17.590
But I want to just mention what
the alternatives come down to.

01:12:17.590 --> 01:12:22.180
They generally randomized
or delegate the selection.

01:12:22.180 --> 01:12:27.220
So rather than saying
any one of 10,000 nodes

01:12:27.220 --> 01:12:31.150
can prove that this
works, they use

01:12:31.150 --> 01:12:33.940
various mathematical means--

01:12:33.940 --> 01:12:37.450
randomized or delegated.

01:12:37.450 --> 01:12:38.920
And sometimes they
do a little bit

01:12:38.920 --> 01:12:42.340
of delegation and
randomization to pick

01:12:42.340 --> 01:12:45.160
who's going to validate
the next block.

01:12:45.160 --> 01:12:50.180
It all comes down to who
is picking the next block.

01:12:50.180 --> 01:12:57.890
Is it by Adam Back's sort of, as
Satoshi Nakamoto put out there,

01:12:57.890 --> 01:13:02.320
we'll call it Nakamoto
consensus, proof of work?

01:13:02.320 --> 01:13:04.480
And you'll have a
paper for Thursday

01:13:04.480 --> 01:13:08.620
that talks about Nakamoto
Consensus, the Clark paper.

01:13:08.620 --> 01:13:13.480
But-- or is there some other
randomized, delegated way

01:13:13.480 --> 01:13:14.080
to do it?

01:13:17.390 --> 01:13:19.730
In some of them, they
have a second check.

01:13:19.730 --> 01:13:22.870
If there's a delegated
person to validate something,

01:13:22.870 --> 01:13:24.960
they put a second check
in there that there's

01:13:24.960 --> 01:13:32.300
another group that officiates
and says whether it's correct.

01:13:32.300 --> 01:13:35.510
And so there's proof of stake,
which is based on the stake

01:13:35.510 --> 01:13:37.340
you have in the
underlying currency.

01:13:37.340 --> 01:13:40.760
There's proof of activity, which
is kind of a hybrid of proof

01:13:40.760 --> 01:13:42.740
of work and proof of stake.

01:13:42.740 --> 01:13:46.850
Proof of burn-- are you
willing to give up coins?

01:13:46.850 --> 01:13:51.960
Proof of capacity-- do
you have storage capacity?

01:13:51.960 --> 01:13:54.360
And you might have
a tiered system.

01:13:54.360 --> 01:13:57.510
The major permissionless
blockchains all use proof

01:13:57.510 --> 01:13:58.570
of work.

01:13:58.570 --> 01:14:00.810
And the reason is
nobody's really solved--

01:14:00.810 --> 01:14:04.180
all of these other
alternatives, no one's

01:14:04.180 --> 01:14:09.130
really solved for a couple
of problems in them.

01:14:09.130 --> 01:14:11.410
But they usually
find a way to be

01:14:11.410 --> 01:14:15.160
more efficient through
delegation and randomization,

01:14:15.160 --> 01:14:18.190
and might have a backup
set of checks on it.

01:14:18.190 --> 01:14:21.430
DASH and NEO will say that
they use proof of stake.

01:14:21.430 --> 01:14:25.860
But they're actually kind of
using some form of masternodes

01:14:25.860 --> 01:14:29.550
or set up professional nodes.

01:14:29.550 --> 01:14:31.780
But DASH and NEO are
kind of, I think,

01:14:31.780 --> 01:14:36.820
the 13th and 15th largest
market value cryptos, which

01:14:36.820 --> 01:14:38.620
means everything else kind of--

01:14:38.620 --> 01:14:39.910
And Ripple doesn't--

01:14:39.910 --> 01:14:43.240
Ripple's really almost like a
permission system rather than

01:14:43.240 --> 01:14:44.080
permissionless.

01:14:44.080 --> 01:14:46.690
I mean, they would say
they're permissionless.

01:14:46.690 --> 01:14:54.170
But it's a confirmed set of
nodes in the node system.

